","1000–Male":"1000–Deceased","1030–Female":"1030–Deceased","about 1050":"about 1050","about 1060":"about 1060","about 1030":"about 1030","1044":"1044","1000":"1000","1042":"1042","1030":"1030","1050":"1050","1093":"1093","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1019":"1019","1047":"1047","1100":"1100","1045":"1045","about 1042":"about 1042","about 1045":"about 1045","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Brecon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire): possibly a habitational name from Breckon Howe in Goathland (North Yorkshire), or from Bracken in Kilnwick (East Yorkshire )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maenyrch ap Dryffin of Brecon was born about 1030, in Breconshire, Wales, his father, Dryffin ap Cudd, was 32 and his mother, Crisli ferch Iago, was 2. He married Elen Verch Einion in 1044, in Wales. He died about 1060, in Wales, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1030–about 1060":"umbes 1030–umbes 1060","1030–1060":"1030–1060","1019–1050":"1019–1050","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1042–Male":"1042–Surnud","1044–1093":"1044–1093","1045–Male":"1045–Surnud","1047–1100":"1047–1100","1050–1100":"1050–1100","–Male":"Surnud","1000–Male":"1000–Surnud","1030–Female":"1030–Surnud","about 1050":"umbes 1050","about 1060":"umbes 1060","about 1030":"umbes 1030","1044":"1044","1000":"1000","1042":"1042","1030":"1030","1050":"1050","1093":"1093","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1019":"1019","1047":"1047","1100":"1100","1045":"1045","about 1042":"umbes 1042","about 1045":"umbes 1045","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales",